<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Having trouble understanding PPUADDR's behavior]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10367&amp;p=116445#p116445"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />you just need to know how to copy/paste some code<br /></div><br />I'm never encouraging anyone to copy/paste code without fully understanding it !!<br /><br />I only did that a couple of times in my life when I really had no choice, but I'd recommend any programmer to stay away of that as much as possible.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />It's complex to understand because it requires familiarity with what the underlying hardware does. Do not let anyone here tell you &quot;it's simple&quot;, because these people already have great familiarity with it -- don't be disheartened by their words.<br /></div><br />I don't have all that much understanding of how the underlying hardware work, and I disagree on saying this is complex, at least not as much as what loopy says (unless you want to know the underlying hardware).<br /><br />All you have to memorize is that the scroll can be seen as two sides of the same same coin.<br />1) The X / Y offset. This is the usual way to understand scrolling. X = [0; 511] and Y = [0; 511] (some of the range of the Y scroll are discouraged as they will display the attribute table as name table, but you probably don't want to do this - but that's another story). Registers $2005 (and lower 2 bits of $2000) view the scroll from this viewpoint.<br />2) The VRAM address. This is a single word that goes ADR = [$2000 ... $2fff]. Reigster $2006 view the scroll from this viewpoint. Note that this very logical since $2006 is used to set VRAM adresses.<br /><br />Now if you want to scroll to a certain position you can either write the X/Y scroll via $2005 or the VRAM adress via $2006, and both of those methods works.<br />HOWEVER, each of those methods have huge drawbacks :<br />$2005/2 (vertical scroll) writes only works during VBlank, so this method is problematic during the frame.<br />$2006 writes can't set the fine scroll within a tile, because you address whole tiles.<br /><br />If you change the scroll outside of VBlank, you can choose between $2005 and $2006. $2005 (and $2000) is good for changing horizontal scrolling, $2006 is good if you want to scroll whole tiles.<br />Now if you want to both change fine scrolling and vertical scrolling, you have to mix $2005 and $2006 writes in a weird way, because only $2005/1 and $2006/2 writes will be taken in account. All other writes will simply be &quot;latched&quot; and have no immediate effect. This is the only part that is &quot;complicated&quot; but it's really quite simple. Just write the values you'd write if you were only writing to $2005, and only to $2006, and it'll work perfectly. You don't have to understand what is the V and T latches or other bullshit to make this work, I can guarantee this to you.<br /><br />I hope this was clear enough to get my idea ^^<br />Everyone on NESDev has been overcomplicating this for years when I figured out that it was in reality quite simple. The only &quot;complex&quot; thing is $2005/2 and $2006/1 writes being ineffective before a $2006/2 write happens.<br /><br />EDIT : Ok I'll have a practical example. Let's say you want to set the scroll to Y = 9 and X = 12 (I just picked random values). This correspond to nametable adress $2021 (one tile left and one tile down).<br /><br />So if you were to write $20 then $21 to $2006 it'd set Y = 8 and X = 8 (in reality it'll set Y = 10 but forget this for now*).<br />If you were to write 12 then 9 to $2005 it'd set X = 9 and Y will remain unnafacted.<br />Both are not what you want.<br />But if you mix them in some way, for example :<br />$2005(/1) = 12<br />$2005(/2) = 9<br />$2005(/1) = 12<br />$2006(/2) = $21<br />it will work.<br /><br />Another alternative would be<br />$2006(/1) = $20<br />$2005(/2) = 9<br />$2005(/1) = 12<br />$2006(/2) = $21<br /><br />or why not<br />$2006(/1) = $10*<br />$2006(/2) = $21<br />$2005(/1) = 9<br /><br />All of them should work, and if they don't there is probably some other orders that will. As long as you keep writing $x0 to $2006(/1), $21 to $2006(/2), and 12 to $2005(/1) and 9 to $2005(/2), you can try any order, and many of them will work. Just trial and error. No need to understand loopy's doc.<br /><br />*) This is another thing to know is that the fine vertical scroll is given by the high nybble of the VRAM adress (normally used to differenciate pattern tables and name tables and palette), I never understood why, it's damn stange, but it's that way. Can only work for scroll values 0 to 3 unfortunately, 4-7 won't work.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> â€” Tue Aug 13, 2013 11:30 am</p><hr />
