<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Having trouble understanding PPUADDR's behavior]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10367&amp;p=116443#p116443"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">IsharaComix wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This subject is confusing as hell for beginners though, and not essential if one doesn't plan on doing mid-screen vertical scroll splits, so don't feel bad if it doesn't make much sense right now.<br /></div><br /><br />That's why I didn't read that document - since I wasn't doing scrolling, I didn't need to worry about scrolling, right? :D<br /><br />When I said unintuitive, I meant unintuitive based on what I've been using as my bible: <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/PPU_registers" class="postlink">the NESDev wiki page on PPU registers</a>. Lots of registers have sneaky little side effects, and you would expect to show up on a major listing page like this. For example, the page happily tells you how to set the PPU pointer using PPUADDR and gives you an example, but doesn't immediately make it clear that you should clean up after you do it.</div><br />It's complex to understand because it requires familiarity with what the underlying hardware does.  Do not let anyone here tell you &quot;it's simple&quot;, because these people already have great familiarity with it -- don't be disheartened by their words.  There is still to this day an immense dichotomy between the hardware-familiar people in nesdev and the software-focused people in nesdev.  Anyway, read this section:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/PPU_scrolling#What_the_registers_do">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/PPU_ ... gisters_do</a><!-- m --><br /><br />If you're anything like me, you'll probably read it the same way I have (and in some regards still do): blah blah, latch blah, Loopy_Blah, single-letter variables, internal blah blah, flip-flop blah blah, and more blah blah.  This is just the nature of the beast with the NES -- when it comes to the PPU, the registers in question are not &quot;fully independent&quot; of other features/things because of how the hardware was designed.  It's like this on even older consoles too (ex. Atari 2600), where everything was even more bare bones.  This document:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/The_skinny_on_NES_scrolling">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/The_ ... _scrolling</a><!-- m --><br /><br />...is a lot more revealing in what all goes on, but it's way too much for the &quot;standard programmer&quot; to take in -- it's overkill in a lot of ways.  But if you read it (and even if you don't understand it all) you'll see that there are continual mentions of what everyone has said -- that $2000, $2002, $2005, and $2006 all share an intricate relationship behind the scenes.<br /><br />There are other consoles where this this stuff is less of a &quot;problem&quot; (for the programmer), and it's one reason I still to this day prefer to code on those other consoles.  IMO, nothing PPU-related on the NES is simple.<br /><br />Since you offer some kind of &quot;online course in NES programming&quot;, I fully support you writing programmer-focused documentation that gradually introduces people to these nuances.  You will end up touching registers even during simple tasks that you didn't think you needed to -- and aren't obviously apparent to your students, prompting them to ask &quot;Why are you doing that?&quot;  You'll have to say &quot;For now just trust me, it's needed&quot; and cover the reason in a later chapter/section (advanced PPU operations, etc.) with references/links to the above stuff.  You can see that the PPU-related parts <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Programming_guide#Tutorials" class="postlink">of the tutorial section of the Wiki</a> are lacking (this is due to people not having the time -- documentation sucks up a lot of time, I speak from experience :P).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3">koitsu</a> â€” Tue Aug 13, 2013 9:55 am</p><hr />
